Note:
MIPS Register Allocator - Register Allocation and Constraint Resolution

This file maps LIR virtual registers to MIPS physical registers according to
the O32 ABI calling convention. MIPS has 32 general-purpose registers ($0-$31)
with specific ABI assignments, plus the HI and LO special registers used by
multiply and divide instructions.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Map LIR virtual registers to MIPS physical GPRs ($0-$31)
- Enforce O32 ABI constraints for argument passing ($a0-$a3) and return ($v0-$v1)
- Track callee-saved ($s0-$s7) and caller-saved ($t0-$t9, $a0-$a3) registers
- Handle HI/LO register constraints for multiply/divide sequences
- Insert spill/reload instructions when register pressure exceeds available GPRs
- Resolve two-address constraints for MIPS pseudo-instructions

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- MIPS register management is crucial for efficient MIPS code generation
- O32 ABI compliance ensures correct function calls and interop with C code
- HI/LO register tracking prevents corruption during multiply/divide sequences
- Register spilling strategy directly impacts generated code performance

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- MIPS register definitions and ABI classification constants
- Register allocation state tracking (free/used/spilled per register)
- O32 ABI argument and return register assignment
- HI/LO register lifetime tracking for multiply/divide
- Spill slot management and stack frame integration
- Post-allocation constraint resolution for MIPS-specific requirements

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for instruction and register definitions
- Imports Layout for memory allocation
- Imports List for collection operations
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIPS REGISTER DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
MIPS has 32 general-purpose registers, each 32 bits wide (or 64 bits in MIPS64).
The O32 ABI assigns specific roles to each register:

  $0  ($zero) - Hardwired to zero, reads always return 0, writes are ignored
  $1  ($at)   - Assembler temporary, reserved for pseudo-instruction expansion
  $2-$3  ($v0-$v1) - Function return values
  $4-$7  ($a0-$a3) - Function arguments (first 4)
  $8-$15 ($t0-$t7) - Temporary registers, caller-saved
  $16-$23 ($s0-$s7) - Saved registers, callee-saved
  $24-$25 ($t8-$t9) - Additional temporaries, caller-saved
  $26-$27 ($k0-$k1) - Kernel reserved, not available to user code
  $28 ($gp) - Global pointer
  $29 ($sp) - Stack pointer
  $30 ($fp/$s8) - Frame pointer / additional saved register
  $31 ($ra) - Return address

Additionally, MIPS has two special-purpose registers:
  HI - High 32 bits of multiply result, or remainder from divide
  LO - Low 32 bits of multiply result, or quotient from divide
@End Reasoning

Note: Register indices matching hardware numbering ($0-$31)
Constant MIPS_REG_ZERO as Integer is 0
Constant MIPS_REG_AT as Integer is 1
Constant MIPS_REG_V0 as Integer is 2
Constant MIPS_REG_V1 as Integer is 3
Constant MIPS_REG_A0 as Integer is 4
Constant MIPS_REG_A1 as Integer is 5
Constant MIPS_REG_A2 as Integer is 6
Constant MIPS_REG_A3 as Integer is 7
Constant MIPS_REG_T0 as Integer is 8
Constant MIPS_REG_T1 as Integer is 9
Constant MIPS_REG_T2 as Integer is 10
Constant MIPS_REG_T3 as Integer is 11
Constant MIPS_REG_T4 as Integer is 12
Constant MIPS_REG_T5 as Integer is 13
Constant MIPS_REG_T6 as Integer is 14
Constant MIPS_REG_T7 as Integer is 15
Constant MIPS_REG_S0 as Integer is 16
Constant MIPS_REG_S1 as Integer is 17
Constant MIPS_REG_S2 as Integer is 18
Constant MIPS_REG_S3 as Integer is 19
Constant MIPS_REG_S4 as Integer is 20
Constant MIPS_REG_S5 as Integer is 21
Constant MIPS_REG_S6 as Integer is 22
Constant MIPS_REG_S7 as Integer is 23
Constant MIPS_REG_T8 as Integer is 24
Constant MIPS_REG_T9 as Integer is 25
Constant MIPS_REG_K0 as Integer is 26
Constant MIPS_REG_K1 as Integer is 27
Constant MIPS_REG_GP as Integer is 28
Constant MIPS_REG_SP as Integer is 29
Constant MIPS_REG_FP as Integer is 30
Constant MIPS_REG_RA as Integer is 31

Note: Total physical register count
Constant MIPS_GPR_COUNT as Integer is 32

Note: Special pseudo-register IDs for HI and LO (not directly addressable)
Constant MIPS_REG_HI as Integer is 32
Constant MIPS_REG_LO as Integer is 33

Note: Register allocation status values
Constant REG_STATUS_FREE as Integer is 0
Constant REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED as Integer is 1
Constant REG_STATUS_RESERVED as Integer is 2
Constant REG_STATUS_SPILLED as Integer is 3

Note: Number of allocatable GPRs (excluding $zero, $at, $k0, $k1, $gp, $sp, $ra)
Constant MIPS_ALLOCATABLE_COUNT as Integer is 25

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER ALLOCATOR STATE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The MIPSRegAllocState tracks the status of all 32 GPRs plus HI/LO. It maintains
a bitmap-style array indicating whether each register is free, allocated, reserved,
or spilled. The state also tracks the current spill offset within the stack frame
and maps LIR virtual registers to physical MIPS registers.

Memory layout (34 entries for 32 GPRs + HI + LO):
  Offset 0..271:   reg_status[34]   - 8 bytes per entry (status code)
  Offset 272..543: lir_mapping[34]  - 8 bytes per entry (LIR vreg mapped here, -1 if none)
  Offset 544:      spill_count      - number of spilled registers
  Offset 552:      spill_offset     - next available spill slot offset from $fp
  Offset 560:      total_size       - 8 bytes
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIPSRegAllocState":
    reg_status as Integer         Note: Pointer to array of 34 status entries (8 bytes each)
    lir_mapping as Integer        Note: Pointer to array of 34 LIR vreg mappings (8 bytes each)
    spill_count as Integer        Note: Number of currently spilled values
    spill_offset as Integer       Note: Next spill slot offset from frame pointer
    callee_saved_used as Integer  Note: Bitmask of callee-saved registers actually used
    hi_in_use as Integer          Note: 1 if HI register contains a live value
    lo_in_use as Integer          Note: 1 if LO register contains a live value
End Type

Note: Size: 7 fields * 8 bytes = 56 bytes per MIPSRegAllocState

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ALLOCATOR INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_mips_reg_alloc_state" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates and initializes the register allocation state. Marks reserved
    registers ($zero, $at, $k0, $k1, $gp, $sp, $ra) as RESERVED so the
    allocator never assigns them. All other registers start as FREE.
    @End Reasoning

    Let state be Layout.allocate(56)
    If state equals 0:
        Display "create_mips_reg_alloc_state: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate status array (34 entries * 8 bytes = 272 bytes)
    Let status_array be Layout.allocate(272)
    If status_array equals 0:
        Display "create_mips_reg_alloc_state: status array allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate LIR mapping array (34 entries * 8 bytes = 272 bytes)
    Let mapping_array be Layout.allocate(272)
    If mapping_array equals 0:
        Display "create_mips_reg_alloc_state: mapping array allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all registers as FREE with no LIR mapping (-1)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 34:
        __store(status_array, i * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        __store(mapping_array, i * 8, -1)
        Set i to i + 1
    End While

    Note: Mark reserved registers that must never be allocated
    Note: $zero ($0) - hardwired zero
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_ZERO * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $at ($1) - assembler temporary
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_AT * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $k0 ($26) - kernel reserved
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_K0 * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $k1 ($27) - kernel reserved
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_K1 * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $gp ($28) - global pointer
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_GP * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $sp ($29) - stack pointer
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_SP * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)
    Note: $ra ($31) - return address (managed by prologue/epilogue)
    __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_RA * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)

    Note: Store pointers and initial values in state struct
    __store(state, 0, status_array)
    __store(state, 8, mapping_array)
    __store(state, 16, 0)     Note: spill_count = 0
    __store(state, 24, 0)     Note: spill_offset = 0
    __store(state, 32, 0)     Note: callee_saved_used = 0
    __store(state, 40, 0)     Note: hi_in_use = 0
    __store(state, 48, 0)     Note: lo_in_use = 0

    Return state
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the given MIPS register is callee-saved per the O32 ABI.
    Callee-saved registers: $s0-$s7 (16-23) and $fp/$s8 (30).
    These must be saved in the function prologue and restored in the epilogue
    if used by the function.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_S0:
        If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_S7:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_FP:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_caller_saved" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the given MIPS register is caller-saved per the O32 ABI.
    Caller-saved registers: $t0-$t7 (8-15), $t8-$t9 (24-25),
    $a0-$a3 (4-7), $v0-$v1 (2-3).
    These are not preserved across function calls.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: $v0-$v1 (2-3)
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_V0:
        If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_V1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Note: $a0-$a3 (4-7)
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_A0:
        If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_A3:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Note: $t0-$t7 (8-15)
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_T0:
        If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_T7:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Note: $t8-$t9 (24-25)
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_T8:
        If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_T9:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_allocatable" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the register can be assigned by the allocator. Excludes:
    $zero (0), $at (1), $k0 (26), $k1 (27), $gp (28), $sp (29), $ra (31).
    @End Reasoning

    If reg equals MIPS_REG_ZERO:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_AT:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_K0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_K1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_GP:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_SP:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals MIPS_REG_RA:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_arg_register" that takes arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the MIPS register used for the given argument index per the O32 ABI.
    Arguments 0-3 go in $a0-$a3. Returns -1 if the argument must be passed on
    the stack (index >= 4).
    @End Reasoning

    If arg_index equals 0:
        Return MIPS_REG_A0
    End If
    If arg_index equals 1:
        Return MIPS_REG_A1
    End If
    If arg_index equals 2:
        Return MIPS_REG_A2
    End If
    If arg_index equals 3:
        Return MIPS_REG_A3
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "get_return_register" that takes ret_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the MIPS register used for the given return value index per O32 ABI.
    Return values go in $v0 (index 0) and $v1 (index 1). Returns -1 for
    invalid indices.
    @End Reasoning

    If ret_index equals 0:
        Return MIPS_REG_V0
    End If
    If ret_index equals 1:
        Return MIPS_REG_V1
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER ALLOCATION OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "allocate_register" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a free physical MIPS register for the given LIR virtual register.
    Allocation priority order:
    1. Temporary registers ($t0-$t7, $t8-$t9) - preferred because caller-saved
       means no save/restore overhead in the common case
    2. Saved registers ($s0-$s7) - used when temporaries exhausted, requires
       save/restore in prologue/epilogue
    3. If no registers available, returns -1 indicating a spill is needed

    The function updates both the status and mapping arrays and tracks which
    callee-saved registers are used so the prologue generator knows what to save.
    @End Reasoning

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)

    Note: First try: temporaries $t0-$t7 (registers 8-15)
    Let reg be MIPS_REG_T0
    While reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_T7:
        Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return reg
        End If
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Second try: temporaries $t8-$t9 (registers 24-25)
    Set reg to MIPS_REG_T8
    While reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_T9:
        Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return reg
        End If
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Third try: saved registers $s0-$s7 (registers 16-23)
    Set reg to MIPS_REG_S0
    While reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_S7:
        Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Note: Mark this callee-saved register as used
            Let used_mask be __load(state, 32)
            Let bit be 1
            Let shift be reg - MIPS_REG_S0
            Let shift_i be 0
            While shift_i is less than shift:
                Set bit to bit * 2
                Set shift_i to shift_i + 1
            End While
            Set used_mask to used_mask + bit
            __store(state, 32, used_mask)
            Return reg
        End If
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Fourth try: frame pointer if not already reserved for frame addressing
    Let fp_status be __load(status_array, MIPS_REG_FP * 8)
    If fp_status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
        __store(status_array, MIPS_REG_FP * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
        __store(mapping_array, MIPS_REG_FP * 8, lir_vreg)
        Let used_mask be __load(state, 32)
        Set used_mask to used_mask + 256
        __store(state, 32, used_mask)
        Return MIPS_REG_FP
    End If

    Note: No free register available - caller must spill
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "free_register" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases a physical register back to the free pool. Clears the allocation
    status and removes the LIR mapping. Returns 1 on success, 0 if the register
    was not allocated or is reserved.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)

    Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
    If status equals REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
    __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, -1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_register_for_lir" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Looks up which physical MIPS register is currently holding the given LIR
    virtual register. Scans the mapping array linearly. Returns the physical
    register index, or -1 if the virtual register is not currently in any
    physical register.
    @End Reasoning

    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)
    Let reg be 0
    While reg is less than 34:
        Let mapped_vreg be __load(mapping_array, reg * 8)
        If mapped_vreg equals lir_vreg:
            Return reg
        End If
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "get_lir_for_register" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the LIR virtual register currently mapped to the given physical
    MIPS register, or -1 if the register is free or reserved.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to 34:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)
    Return __load(mapping_array, reg * 8)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SPILL MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "spill_register" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Spills the contents of a physical register to a stack slot. Returns the
    spill slot offset (negative from $fp). The caller is responsible for
    emitting the actual sw/lw instructions; this function only manages the
    bookkeeping of spill slot assignment.

    Spill slots are allocated in 4-byte increments (word-aligned for MIPS O32).
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
    If status does not equal REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Assign next spill slot
    Let spill_count be __load(state, 16)
    Let spill_off be __load(state, 24)
    Set spill_off to spill_off - 4
    Set spill_count to spill_count + 1

    __store(state, 16, spill_count)
    __store(state, 24, spill_off)
    __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_SPILLED)

    Return spill_off
End Process

Process called "reload_register" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer, spill_offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks a register as allocated again after a reload from its spill slot.
    The caller emits the actual lw instruction; this function updates the
    allocation status. Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_spill_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 16)
End Process

Process called "get_total_spill_size" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the total number of bytes needed for spill slots. This is used
    to compute the stack frame size. Each spill slot is 4 bytes on MIPS O32.
    @End Reasoning

    Let count be __load(state, 16)
    Return count * 4
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HI/LO REGISTER MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "mark_hi_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks the HI register as containing a live value. Called after mult or div
    instructions that write to HI. The allocator must not insert any instructions
    between a mult/div and the mfhi that reads the result if HI is live.
    @End Reasoning

    __store(state, 40, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_lo_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks the LO register as containing a live value. Called after mult or div
    instructions that write to LO.
    @End Reasoning

    __store(state, 48, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_hi_free" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(state, 40, 0)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_lo_free" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(state, 48, 0)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_hi_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 40)
End Process

Process called "is_lo_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 48)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CALLEE-SAVED REGISTER TRACKING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_callee_saved_used_mask" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a bitmask of callee-saved registers that were allocated during
    this function. Bit 0 = $s0, bit 1 = $s1, ..., bit 7 = $s7, bit 8 = $fp.
    The prologue generator uses this to determine which registers to save/restore.
    @End Reasoning

    Return __load(state, 32)
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Counts the number of callee-saved registers that were used. This determines
    how many extra stack slots the prologue needs to allocate for register saves.
    @End Reasoning

    Let mask be __load(state, 32)
    Let count be 0
    While mask is greater than 0:
        Let bit be mask - ((mask / 2) * 2)
        Set count to count + bit
        Set mask to mask / 2
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_by_index" that takes state as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the physical register number of the Nth callee-saved register that
    was used (0-indexed). This is used by the prologue/epilogue generator to
    iterate over callee-saved registers in order.
    @End Reasoning

    Let mask be __load(state, 32)
    Let count be 0
    Let bit_pos be 0
    While bit_pos is less than 9:
        Let bit be mask - ((mask / 2) * 2)
        If bit equals 1:
            If count equals index:
                Note: Map bit position back to register number
                If bit_pos is less than 8:
                    Return MIPS_REG_S0 + bit_pos
                End If
                Return MIPS_REG_FP
            End If
            Set count to count + 1
        End If
        Set mask to mask / 2
        Set bit_pos to bit_pos + 1
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER NAME LOOKUP
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_gpr_name" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the string name of a MIPS GPR by its hardware number.
    Uses standard MIPS register naming: $zero, $at, $v0-$v1, $a0-$a3,
    $t0-$t7, $s0-$s7, $t8-$t9, $k0-$k1, $gp, $sp, $fp, $ra.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg equals 0:
        Return "$zero"
    End If
    If reg equals 1:
        Return "$at"
    End If
    If reg equals 2:
        Return "$v0"
    End If
    If reg equals 3:
        Return "$v1"
    End If
    If reg equals 4:
        Return "$a0"
    End If
    If reg equals 5:
        Return "$a1"
    End If
    If reg equals 6:
        Return "$a2"
    End If
    If reg equals 7:
        Return "$a3"
    End If
    If reg equals 8:
        Return "$t0"
    End If
    If reg equals 9:
        Return "$t1"
    End If
    If reg equals 10:
        Return "$t2"
    End If
    If reg equals 11:
        Return "$t3"
    End If
    If reg equals 12:
        Return "$t4"
    End If
    If reg equals 13:
        Return "$t5"
    End If
    If reg equals 14:
        Return "$t6"
    End If
    If reg equals 15:
        Return "$t7"
    End If
    If reg equals 16:
        Return "$s0"
    End If
    If reg equals 17:
        Return "$s1"
    End If
    If reg equals 18:
        Return "$s2"
    End If
    If reg equals 19:
        Return "$s3"
    End If
    If reg equals 20:
        Return "$s4"
    End If
    If reg equals 21:
        Return "$s5"
    End If
    If reg equals 22:
        Return "$s6"
    End If
    If reg equals 23:
        Return "$s7"
    End If
    If reg equals 24:
        Return "$t8"
    End If
    If reg equals 25:
        Return "$t9"
    End If
    If reg equals 26:
        Return "$k0"
    End If
    If reg equals 27:
        Return "$k1"
    End If
    If reg equals 28:
        Return "$gp"
    End If
    If reg equals 29:
        Return "$sp"
    End If
    If reg equals 30:
        Return "$fp"
    End If
    If reg equals 31:
        Return "$ra"
    End If
    Return "$zero"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FULL ALLOCATION RESET
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "reset_allocation" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resets the allocation state for a new function. Clears all register
    allocations but preserves the reserved register markings. Resets
    spill counters and HI/LO usage flags.
    @End Reasoning

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)

    Let reg be 0
    While reg is less than 34:
        Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
        If status does not equal REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
            __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        End If
        __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, -1)
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While

    __store(state, 16, 0)  Note: spill_count = 0
    __store(state, 24, 0)  Note: spill_offset = 0
    __store(state, 32, 0)  Note: callee_saved_used = 0
    __store(state, 40, 0)  Note: hi_in_use = 0
    __store(state, 48, 0)  Note: lo_in_use = 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "assign_specific_register" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Forces a specific physical register to be assigned to a LIR virtual register.
    Used for ABI-required assignments (e.g., $a0 for first argument, $v0 for
    return value). If the register is already allocated to a different vreg,
    the existing mapping is evicted (caller must handle spilling if needed).
    Returns 1 on success, 0 if the register is reserved.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let status_array be __load(state, 0)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 8)

    Let status be __load(status_array, reg * 8)
    If status equals REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(status_array, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
    __store(mapping_array, reg * 8, lir_vreg)

    Note: Track callee-saved usage
    If is_callee_saved(reg) equals 1:
        Let used_mask be __load(state, 32)
        Let bit_pos be 0
        If reg is greater than or equal to MIPS_REG_S0:
            If reg is less than or equal to MIPS_REG_S7:
                Set bit_pos to reg - MIPS_REG_S0
            End If
        End If
        If reg equals MIPS_REG_FP:
            Set bit_pos to 8
        End If
        Let bit be 1
        Let shift_i be 0
        While shift_i is less than bit_pos:
            Set bit to bit * 2
            Set shift_i to shift_i + 1
        End While
        Note: Only set the bit if not already set (avoid double-counting)
        Let test_val be used_mask / bit
        Let test_bit be test_val - ((test_val / 2) * 2)
        If test_bit equals 0:
            Set used_mask to used_mask + bit
            __store(state, 32, used_mask)
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process
